<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<exercises xml:id="ex_intro_robotics" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Chapter 1 Exercises</title>

  <!-- Section 1.1 Exercises -->
  <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup_what_is_robotics">
    <title>Introduction to Robotics</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_robot_definition">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the four key characteristics that define a robot? Provide a brief 
          explanation of each.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Review the subsection on "Defining a Robot" in Section 1.1.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The four key characteristics are: (1) Sensing - ability to perceive the 
          environment through sensors, (2) Processing - capability to process sensor 
          data and make decisions, (3) Actuation - means to physically interact with 
          the environment, and (4) Autonomy - some degree of independent operation 
          without constant human control.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_robot_applications">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose two different application areas of robotics (e.g., manufacturing, 
          healthcare, exploration) and describe one specific challenge that robots 
          face in each area.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_robot_vs_automation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain the difference between a robot and a simple automated machine. 
          Give an example of each.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <!-- Section 1.2 Exercises -->
  <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup_subsystems">
    <title>Robot Subsystems</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_subsystems_identify">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For a mobile warehouse robot, identify and describe the function of at least 
          one component from each of the following subsystems:
          <ol>
            <li>Mechanical structure and actuation</li>
            <li>Sensors and perception</li>
            <li>Computation and processing</li>
            <li>Power supply</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_sensors_categories">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Classify each of the following sensors as either proprioceptive or 
          exteroceptive, and explain why:
          <ol>
            <li>Wheel encoder</li>
            <li>Camera</li>
            <li>IMU (Inertial Measurement Unit)</li>
            <li>LIDAR</li>
            <li>Force/torque sensor</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          (1) Wheel encoder - Proprioceptive (measures internal joint position),
          (2) Camera - Exteroceptive (perceives external environment),
          (3) IMU - Proprioceptive (measures internal acceleration and angular velocity),
          (4) LIDAR - Exteroceptive (measures distances to external objects),
          (5) Force/torque sensor - Proprioceptive (measures forces applied to the robot's own joints)
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_actuator_selection">
      <statement>
        <p>
          You are designing a small educational robot that needs to move on wheels 
          and has a gripper to pick up lightweight objects. What type of actuators 
          would you choose for (a) wheel movement and (b) the gripper? Justify your choices.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <!-- Section 1.3 Exercises -->
  <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup_ppc_loop">
    <title>Perception-Planning-Control Loop</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_ppc_example">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Describe the perception-planning-control loop for an autonomous vacuum 
          cleaning robot. For each stage (perception, planning, control), explain 
          what information is processed and what outputs are generated.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_loop_timing">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain why different parts of a robot's control system might need to run 
          at different loop rates. Give examples of tasks that require fast loops 
          (1-10 ms) versus tasks that can use slower loops (100-1000 ms).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Consider what might happen if a motor control loop runs too slowly, or if 
          a path planning algorithm tries to run too quickly.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_feedback_importance">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why is feedback critical in the perception-planning-control loop? What 
          would happen if a robot executed actions without ever sensing the results?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <!-- Section 1.4 Exercises -->
  <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup_control_fundamentals">
    <title>Control Fundamentals</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_openloop_closedloop">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each scenario below, determine whether open-loop or closed-loop control 
          would be more appropriate and explain why:
          <ol>
            <li>A robotic arm painting a pre-programmed pattern on a stationary surface</li>
            <li>A drone maintaining a fixed altitude in windy conditions</li>
            <li>A microwave oven heating food for a set time</li>
            <li>A mobile robot navigating to a specific location in a warehouse</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_closedloop_components">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Draw a block diagram of a closed-loop control system for controlling the 
          speed of a robot's wheels. Label all components: reference input, controller, 
          actuator, plant, sensor, and error signal.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_openloop_limitations">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A robot is programmed to move forward by running its motors at a constant 
          speed for 5 seconds (open-loop control). List three real-world factors 
          that could cause the robot to not travel the expected distance, and explain 
          how closed-loop control could compensate for each factor.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Possible factors include: (1) Friction variations - closed-loop control 
          measures actual position and adjusts speed to compensate, (2) Battery 
          voltage drop - feedback ensures consistent speed regardless of voltage,
          (3) Surface slope - position feedback allows the controller to adjust for 
          uphill/downhill movement, (4) Wheel slippage - encoders detect if wheels 
          spin without moving the robot. Other valid answers include load changes, 
          obstacles, or motor wear.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_error_calculation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A robot is commanded to move to position <m>x = 100</m> cm. Currently, 
          it is at position <m>x = 35</m> cm. Calculate the error signal. If the 
          robot is moving at 10 cm/s toward the target, what will the error be 
          after 3 seconds?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <!-- Section 1.5 Exercises -->
  <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup_pid">
    <title>PID Control</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_pid_terms">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Describe in your own words what each term of a PID controller does:
          <ol>
            <li>Proportional (P) term</li>
            <li>Integral (I) term</li>
            <li>Derivative (D) term</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_p_controller_calculation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A robot uses a proportional controller with <m>K_p = 0.8</m> to control 
          its position. Calculate the control output <m>u(t)</m> for each of the 
          following errors:
          <ol>
            <li><m>e(t) = 10</m> cm</li>
            <li><m>e(t) = 5</m> cm</li>
            <li><m>e(t) = 0.5</m> cm</li>
          </ol>
          What do you notice about the control output as the error decreases?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          (1) <m>u = 0.8 \times 10 = 8</m>,
          (2) <m>u = 0.8 \times 5 = 4</m>,
          (3) <m>u = 0.8 \times 0.5 = 0.4</m>.
          The control output decreases proportionally with the error, which means 
          the robot slows down as it approaches the target.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_integral_purpose">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain why a proportional controller alone often results in steady-state 
          error. How does adding an integral term solve this problem?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_derivative_effect">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A robot is approaching its target position quickly. Explain how the 
          derivative term in a PID controller helps prevent the robot from 
          overshooting the target.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_pid_tuning">
      <statement>
        <p>
          You are tuning a PID controller for a robot's position control. Currently, 
          the robot reaches the target position but oscillates back and forth around 
          it for several seconds before settling. Which PID gain(s) should you adjust 
          and in which direction (increase or decrease) to reduce the oscillations?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Consider which term provides damping to reduce oscillations.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p>
          You should increase the derivative gain (<m>K_d</m>) to add damping and 
          reduce oscillations. Alternatively, you could decrease the proportional 
          gain (<m>K_p</m>), though this would also slow down the initial response. 
          If integral gain (<m>K_i</m>) is high, reducing it might also help.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_pid_implementation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a discrete-time PID controller running at 10 Hz (every 0.1 seconds). 
          Write the equations for calculating each of the three terms (P, I, D) in 
          discrete time at time step <m>k</m>, given the current error <m>e[k]</m> 
          and previous error <m>e[k-1]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <!-- Comprehensive Exercises -->
  <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup_comprehensive">
    <title>Comprehensive Problems</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_system_design">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Design a complete control system for a line-following robot that uses a 
          light sensor to detect its position relative to a dark line on a light surface. 
          Your answer should include:
          <ol>
            <li>What sensor(s) would you use and why?</li>
            <li>What would be measured (the controlled variable)?</li>
            <li>What would be the actuators?</li>
            <li>Would you use open-loop or closed-loop control? Why?</li>
            <li>If using PID control, which terms (P, I, D) would be most important and why?</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_compare_scenarios">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compare and contrast how each of the following robot systems uses the 
          perception-planning-control loop. Identify the key sensors, planning 
          challenges, and control requirements for each:
          <ol>
            <li>An industrial robot welding car parts on an assembly line</li>
            <li>An autonomous delivery drone</li>
            <li>A surgical robot assisting in minimally invasive surgery</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex_real_world_analysis">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Research a real robot system (such as the Mars Perseverance rover, Boston 
          Dynamics' Spot robot, or an autonomous car). Write a short report (1-2 pages) 
          describing:
          <ol>
            <li>The robot's main subsystems and their functions</li>
            <li>How the perception-planning-control loop operates in this system</li>
            <li>What control strategies are likely used (and at what levels)</li>
            <li>Key challenges this robot faces and how its design addresses them</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

</exercises>
